{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_1kahlo_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280602048/1937102101/0133.xml":{"full_text":"G.O.P. Lacks\nAffirmative\nProgram\nVictory Is Doubted\nWithout Definite\nPlan to Offer.\n\nBY DAVYD LAWRENCE.\nWHILE former Gov. Landon\nmade an interesting and\nrather persuasive speech\nof the negative variety\u2014\nproving that the New Deal and Presi\ndent Roosevelt have made mistakes\u2014\nthere was little, if anything, of con\nstructively affirmative value In the\nutterance by the standard bearer of\nthe Republican party.\nThe Republican spokesmen are still\nClinging to the notion that all that is\nnecessary to dislodge the Democrats\nfrom power is to call attention to their\nerrors. If Mr. Landon's address was\nlisit'ixeu tu uv ixxe\n17.000,000 who\nvoted, as he said,\nfor the Repub\nlican cause last\nAutumn, then it;\nwould seem su-!\nperfluous to tell\nthem over again j\nwhy the Demo-\ncratic cause is i\nobjectionable.\nThere may be?\npretty general\nagreement among ;i\nRepublicans, i n i\nfact an almost'\nunanimous opin\njuii, indb ivir. rtooseven nas vioiaiea\nthe spirit and the letter of constitu\ntional government in America and\nmany of the 7,000,000 independent\nvoters who hold the balance of power\nand who voted for Mr. Roosevelt last\ntime may be now In the mood to agree\nalso, but this does not mean that the\nsame independent voters are ready to\naccept a Republican candidate without\na program or a Republican party with\nout a fundamentally sincere and prac\ntical formula for restoring to the\noverage man the job he once held or\nthe standard of living he once en\njoyed.\nAim Only to Criticize.\nThe Republicans, for instance, who\neould boast about the high wage levels\nthat prevailed during their years of\nincumbency, are not telling the voters\nhow those levels now may be attained\nor how the unemployment problem\nran be solved. There is. in fact, no\nInclination yet in Republican circles\nto do anything but criticize the ad\nministration and to repeat that criti\ncism in more and more vehement\nterms as the New Deal drifts on\nthrough a staggering load of debt and\ns calm indifference to the needs of\nthe business situation.\nA sort of 4*i\u201crioration has entered\nthe domain of politics In recent years\nand the Democrats are not better than\nthe Republicans. The administration\nand Its spokesmen resort, for instance,\nflmost constantly to name calling or\nthe imputing of bad motives to their\nopponents. The Republicans simply\nrepeat that the New Deal 4s bent on\ndestroying America.\nThe character of the argument\nwould seem to have been dictated by\ns peculiar notion of what the mentality\nof the American citizen really is.\nPerhaps the political leaders are taking\ntheir cue from the statement made a\nfew years ago that the average men\ntality of the radio listener was about\n12 years of age or less. Undoubtedly\nradio has tended to cause otherwise\nintelligent leaders to effect some kind\nof an artificial expression which talks\ndown to the people or seeks to appeal\nonly to their emotions or sense of\nindignation.\n7,000,000 Saw Selves Liberals.\nThe 7,000,000 Independent voters\nwho helped to elect Mr. Roosevelt be\ncause they thought he was a better\nbet than Mr. Landon might, for pur\nposes of appraisal, be assumed to be\ndifferent from the 20,000.000 who re\nceived direct benefits from the New\nDeal.\nToday such an independent group\u2014\nand I use 7,000,000 merely as an\nillustration of the possible strength of\nthe independents\u2014may think Mr.\nRoosevelt is overshooting the mark,\nbut they are not yet ready to turn over\nthe immense powers of the Federal\nGovernment to those who merely\ncriticize.\nThe most constructive suggestion\nthat has come out of the Republican\nranks\u2014inadequate thought it be\u2014is\nthat the entity called the Republican\nparty have a midterm convention and\net least see whether it can agree on\nsome basic principles. But this idea\nhas been bandied about and frowned\nupon by the politicians in the Republi\ncan party as too risky. Certainly it is\nrisky to take a position and be positive\nif your philosophy in life is to be all\nthings to all people. It was risky in\nthe Cleveland convention of 1936 to\nstrike out forthrightly instead of ac\ncepting weak compromises. It is\nrisky to delve into all the major\nproblems of the day and attempt a\nsolution, but a party that doesn't care\nto use the intellectual approach and\nmolds its course to meet the lowest\ncommon denominator of voter intelli\ngence instead of the highest is making\nan error of incalculable damage to\nItself.\nIndependents People of Brains.\nThe independents are the people of\nbrains who read newspapers and mag\nazines and who cannot be persuaded\nby overemotional appeals. Mr. Lan\ndon w\u2019ould have done better if he had\navoided the radio and issued a state\nment of constructive suggestions on\nUnemployment insurance, social se\ncurity, labor relations, expansion of\nthe capital goods industries and anti\nmonopoly legislation, to mention only.\na few of the topics of the hour.\nThe country is waiting for an alter\nnative leadership in specific terms.\nThe midterm convention, if the Re\npublicans can summon enough cour\nage to hold one, may be the beginning\nof such a trend, but with such a con\nvention should go a thorough study\nof each of the topics of major interest\nend some alternative suggestions.\nIf the Republicans are lacking in\nIdeas, let them get copies of the nu\nmerous memoranda and reports sub\nmitted by the so-called Business and\nAdvisory Council of the Department\nof Commerce, sometimes called the\nRoper council. All they need for a\nprogram and platform is to accept\nthe proposals which Mr. Roosevelt has\nin season and out of season rejected\nbecause they happen to be inconsistent\nwith his notion of politics or his cru\nsade for personal power. The pigeon\nholes of Government offices here are\nfull of proposals on every subject of\ncurrent interest, proposals worked out\nin unpolitical mood and without par\ntisanship.\nSome day the Republican party will\ndiscover that Intellectual leadership\nwins independent votes, and that\n\"talking down\u201d to the crowd and\n\"calling names\u201d doesn\u2019t win elections.\n(Copyright, 1937.) I\nr j\nDavid Lawrence.\nWhat\u2019s Back of It AU\nFish Hopes to Push His Own Neutrality Bill With\nCampaign in House.\nBY H. R. BALKHAGE.\nHEN Hamilton Fish gets on the air Friday night and charges\nthat Franklin Roosevelt is another Woodrow Wilson, leading us\ninto the shambles of a world war, the Republican Representa\ntive hopes to light a fuse leading right into the middle of\nthe special session.\nWaiting for signatures on the Speaker's desk is a petition for the\ndischarge of the committee which is sitting bn Mr. Fish's own neutrality\nbill. That piece of legislation is\nshort and sweet, and, if passed,\nwould force the President to \u201cbe\nneutral\u2019\u2019 whether or no. It would\nstop shipment of all arms and am\nmunition to anybody, anywhere,\nany time.\nMr. Fish explains that the act\nwas introduced to meet a specific\ncase, i. e., the Far Eastern trouble.\nBut once the situation changed, it\ncould, if necessary, be repealed.\n\nAs ranking Republican and oldest member in point of service\non the House Foreign Affairs Committee, Mr. Fish purports to speak\nfor the Republican party on international relations. It has been hinted\nhe may organize and lead a neutrality drive in the House.\n\nMeanwhile, the pro-neutrality crowd, inside and outside of the State\nDepartment, is still hopeful that it might w'ake up some morning and find\nthe law invoked. The idea being, if we did invoke the law and thus went\non record as neutral between China and Japan, it might help, rather than\nhurt, in getting some co-operation from Japan in the nine-power treaty\nnegotiations.\nIt is Interesting to note (and Japan has probably noted it) that the\nState Department officials who are in favor of Invoking the neutrality law\nare being referred to frequently and generally as \u201cpro-Japanese\" by some\nof their colleagues.\nik\nHow the Supreme Court\u2019s changing its mind has affected an impor\ntant conference which opens at the Labor Department on Thursday can\nnow be told.\nThe conferees, headed by Secretary of Labor Perkins and repre\nsentatives of the Women\u2019s Bureau, are officials from the 24 States, Including\nPuerto Rico, which have minimum wage laws for women.\nBack in 1923. the Supreme Court said that the District of Columbia\nlaw, which prescribed a minimum wage for women based on the cost of\nliving, was unconstitutional. In 1936. it held invalid a New York law which\nfixed such wages on the basis of fair value of services rendered.\n\nHowever, when the Washington State law was tested in the\ncourt in 1937 it was upheld. Legal experts interpreted the decisions\nas being so broad as not to bar any particular method by which\na State may arrive at the minimum wage it permits.\n\nToday, 10 such State laws have a \u201ccost of living\u201d determination of a\nminimum wage, four name a flat rate, seven prescribe a \"fair value of\nservices rendered,\u201d while three have held the fair value and cost of living\nbasis.\nThis is the seventh conference of Federal-State minimum wage offi\ncials. But it is the first one to discuss the cost of living as a basis for setting\nminimum wage standards.\nIn other words, the growing\nconcern of the State minimum\nwage boards in trying to arrive at\na minimum pay rate, regardless of\nthe provisions of their particular\nlaws, appears to be how much it\ncosts a woman worker to live.\nTo aid in this discussion the\nFederal bureau has worked out a\ndetailed list of the items which\nshould go into a woman's budget,\nincluding even the number of hats,\nshoes, dresses and the like that she must buy in a year. It has not. however,\nset prioes on these articles, leaving that to the States, in view of a wide\nvariation of prices.\n\nHere is the way one New Deal adviser, just returned from abroad, sums\nup the effect of the President's Chicago speech on European ears:\n\u201cThe stop-war negotiations in Europe had become so involved in\ntactics that a definite strategy was lost. Everything was centered on the\nnext move. The speech put the French-British efforts back on the broad\nbasis of a general strategy again\u2014got them out of the mess of tactics.\"\n(Copyright. 1937, by the North American Newspaper Alliance, Inc.)\n\ndebunking dunking\nWO. I IT WILKINS COFrtl 4 Ttt\n\"THE SKEET DUNK\"\nIf you miss practically\nevery bird you shoot at\n(as icc do), try this with,\nyour Wilkins CoffeeI\n\nI 3-Piece Suite, Veneered\nWalnut, Simmons Coil\nSpring, Innerspring Mattress\nSensational bedroom outfit offer! Wonderful three-piece\nmodern design bedroom suite with lovely mirrors and ^^B\nother quality features, with many extras included with- ^MB\nout charge! Here's exactly what you get: a BH\nif Full Size Bed Simmons Coil Spring\nif Chest of Drawers Innerspring Mattress\nif Dresser or Vanity $1 A WEEK!\nSesday I\nday\nVI.\u2014\n)ay 1\n.M.\n\n1245 Wise. Ave. N.W.\nFree\nDelivery\nWithin\nSO Miles\n'THE opinions 0} the writers on this page are their own. not\n1 necessarily The Star's. Such opinions are presented in\nThe Star's effort to give all sides of questions 0/ interest to its\nreaders, although such opinions may he contradictory among\nthemselves and directly opposed to The Star\u2019s.\nStocks Deny Recovery\nSlump Challenges Roosevelt Belief Need of Pump\nPriming Has Disappeared.\nBY MARK SULLIVAN.\nON Monday afternoon Presi\ndent Roosevelt, In the course\nof a statement about the\nbudget, announced that he\nhad given directions to wind up two\nof the great agencies for recovery\nthrough spending. The Public Works\nAdmin istration\nwas to take on no\nnew projects, and\nno existing com\nmitments were to\nbe increased. A\nsimilar announce\nment was made\nabout tlie Recon\nstruction Finance\nCorporation.\nAbout the same\ntime, important\nmembers of the\nadmin istration j\nwho had talked\nwith the Presi\nrlmt declared\npublicly that he was determined to\nbalance the budget. All the atmos\nphere, the whole emphasis, was on\nending the period of spending in order\nto bring recovery. Underlying the new\npolicy, presumably, was the theory\nthat recovery is here. That \u2018\u2018pump\npriming\u201d and other depression ex\npenditures were no longer necessary.\nThen on Tuesday came one of\nthe most sensational price-drops the\nsecurities markets have ever had. The\nfall was of proportions which, in past\nexperience, have usually heralded\nrather marked recessions in business.\nDecidedly the stock market was not\nsaying that recovery is here. Rather it\nwas saying the opposite.\nCause and Effect Jumbled.\nLet us not read any necessary mean\ning into the coincidence of Mr. Roose\nvelt\u2019s assumption that recovery is here\nwith the securities market indication\nthat some degree of business recession\nis ahead. Between the two incidents\nis no necessary relation of cause and\neffect. Such a relation may be there,\nbut no one can be certain it is. Much\nof the fallacious thinking currently\nafflicting the world arises from mis\ntakenly assuming a relation of cause\nand effect between events which have\nno such relation or only a slight one.\nBut the stock market slump raises\nsome interesting questions about bal\nancing the budget, and about Mr.\nRoosevelt's policies generally. The\nstock market slump is not much taken\ninto account yet except by persons\nclosely concerned. Readers of news\npapers distant from the great cities\nare hardly aware that anything has\nhappened or that it means anything\nto them. But nearly all experience\nsuggests that a market slump of this\nextent is followed fairly soon by re\ncession in volume of general business,\nincluding, of course, some increase\nin unemployment. Indeed this is fore\ncast by other indexes, such as the\ndrop In activity In the steel industry.\nRecession Hits Budget Balance.\nIf there is marked increase of un\nemployment, what will be the reaction\nof Congress, the President and the\ncountry? Will Mr. Roosevelt continue\nin determination to balance the\nbudget? Balancing the budget is\nmade more difficult by business reces\nsion in two ways. Increase of unem\nployment leads to demand for Govern\nment expenditure to take care of it.\nWill Congress be in a mood to call\nfor more expenditures, more public\nworks, more borrowing, a new install\nment of pump-priming? New bor\nrowing at a time when the national\ndebt is about 35 billion dollars is a\ndifficult matter from borrowing when\nthe national debt was only about 22\nbillion dollars, as it was about the\ntirfte the Roosevelt administration\nbegan.\nAnd unemployment, and the taking\ncare of^unemployment, at a time when\nthe cost of living is high, is a different\nmatter from unemployment at a time\nwhen the cost of living was low, as it\nwas when Mr. Roosevelt embarked on\nthe principle that the Federal Govern\nment must make itself responsible for\nthe unemployed.\nIf there is a business recession\nsufficient to cause the public to be\nunpleasnatly conscious of it\u2014will the\ncountry, under that condition, and\naware of the high cast of living\u2014will\nthe country be sympathetic to a policy\nof crop control, which means paying\nfarmers cash from the public Treasury\nfor not raising food?\nPossible Questions.\nIf there Is business recession and un\nemployment sufficiently marked to\nhave political effects, and if President\nRoosevelt is reproached for having\nfailed to bring dependable recovery,\nwhat will be his attitude? Will he\ntake refuge in pointing an accusatory\nfinger toward other quarters? Will he\nsay that the recovery he promised was\ndefeated only because some of his\nmeasures were frustrated? Will he\nsay, in effect, that if he had got his\nmeasure to change the Supreme Court,\nand if he had been allowed to keep\nN. R. A. and A. A. A., he would in\nthat event have brought assured\neconomic happiness? And will he now\nask once more for those measures or\ntheir equivalents? And if he takes\nthat line, how will Congress and the\ncountry feel about it? Will they be\ninclined to give him greater powers?\nOr will they feel that his way of\nbringing recovery has not worked?\nWill they be disillusioned about his\nmagic and turn away from him?\nIn all this there is much \"if.\u201d and\nmuch more question than answer.\nAbout all we can say is that a business\nrecession might charge the political\npicture, and mark the beginning of a\nnew phase of the era in which we\nhave been for several years.\n(Copyright. 1837.)\nMark Sallivan.\nWe, the People\nNew Musical Comedy Ridiculing President\u2019s Family Is\nHeld Unfair Because He Can\u2019t Strike Back.\nBY J. FRANKLIN.\nBACK In the Spring of 1933 I recall hearing a very elaborate hard\nluck gtory of how Republican official* were hounding the author\nand printer of a book called \u201cThe Strange Career of President\nHoover Under Two Flags.\u201d The book was cheap enough, but it\npretended to be a recital of established facts calculated to damage the\npolitical standing of the President of the United States and great efforts\nwere made to suppress it.\nStill earlier, when 1 was on the Sunday saff of the New York\nTimes, I reoollect how Republican pressure was brought to bear to\ninduce us to play down Samuel Hopkins Adams' novel, \"Revelry,\"\nthe best fictional account of the barbaric horseplay of the Harding\nadministration, and how \"The President's daughter\" was denied\nadequate review.\nJust before the deluge came \u201cOf The I Sing!\u201d an amusing musical\nsatire on American politics which avoided personalities like the plague.\nI wonder\u2014or rather I do not\nwonder, for I know\u2014what would\nhave happened to any playwright\nor producer or theater owner who\nhad proposed, during the 12 years\nof Republican control at Wash\nington, to stage a play which pub\nlicly burlesqued Mr. and Mrs.\nCoolidge or Mr. and Mrs. Hoover\nand their respective families. It\nwould quietly have been suppressed\nfrom the start, as a calculated\ninsult to the dignity and the office of the President of the United States.\n\nNow we have a bright new musical play, which opened before the\nJingling money-changers of the American Bankers' Association at Boston,\n\u201cI'd Rather Be Right!\u201d With an antiquated song-and-dance man in the\nlead, this production deliberately burlesques not only President Roosevelt\nand his cabinet (who may be legitimate subjects for theatrical cartooning)\nbut also his wife and his mother.\nThis goes beyond political license and raises the issue of common\ndecency and good taste.\nOnly at the risk of raising a hullabaloo against \"censorship\ncan a mail in Mr. Roosevelt's position take steps to protect the ladies\no) his household from public and intentional mockery. This is\nhitting below the belt,\nI am not for drawing a magic circle of unctuous President-worship\naround Mr. Roosevelt or any other Chief Executive. He is a political\nleader, a dynamic and picturesque personality, a reformer who has\noffended many powerful Interests.\n\nThat he should be vilified and lampooned by those who seek to drag\nhim down is perhaps natural: it is certainly inevitable at this stage in\nour political evolution. He can take it and the chances are that it will\nstrengthen his political standing with the mass of the people.\nWhat arouses my curiosity is the mentality of the men who\nemploy such childish methods of political argument and who are\nprepared to throw mud at the head of the American Nation and to\ndiscredit his high office as soon as it can no longer be controlled in\nthe interest of the tax dodgers de luxe.\nSuppose the Communist party were to produce a play making a\nsimilar attack on the person, the office and the family of the Chief\nExecutive. We all know how eagerly the police would wade in to stop\nthe performance.\n\nYet here we find the bankers,\nwhose business is based on Fed\neral authority, whose safety de\npends on \u201claw and order,\u201d and\nwhose very hides Mr. Roosevelt\nsaved four short years ago, guf\nfawing fulsomely at a calculated\nmockery of the men and institu\ntions which saved them. Per\nhaps the philosopher was right\nwhen he observed that the Bour\nbons learn nothing and forget\nnothing.\nSo let George M. Cohan Jibe and caper before the silk-stocking gang,\nlet Hollywood rush to put It on the screen so that everybody can get a\nglimpse of the Tory mind in action. There are said to be good gags in\nthe show and no doubt the songs go over with a swing, but when all is\nsaid and done, \"I'd Rather Be Right!\" shows that the economic potentates\nare down to the last argument of the worsted guttersnipe: Insults to the\nwomenfolk of the man who has offended them.\n(Copyright, 1937.)\nAn American\nYou Should\nCharles West Has Dual\nJob With Interior\nand White House.\nBY DELIA PYNCHON.\nIN ONE of the new de luxe De\npartment of Interior suites,\nleather upholstered, rose eur\ntanied, Charles West carries on\nhis two-fold job. He Is Under Secre\ntary of Interior, a position created for\nhim by the President In 1935. He Is\nliaison officer be\ntween the White\nHouse and Con\ngress.\nHU work In\nInterior may be\ndescribed as su\npervisory, admin\nUtrativc, policy\nforming. He is\nenthusiastic\nabout the work\nof the 15 bureaus,\nwith their diver\nsity of conserva\ntion interest*. He\nU \"loco parentis\u201d\nwhen the Secre\nvary is out oi rown\njust returned from a trip West\nwith a quick glimpse at some of thl\nPublic Works projects. Mr. West spoke\nat Albuquerque and El Paso.\n\"I bragged about the accomplish*\nmeats of the New Deal,\" Mr. West\nsaid with his expansive smile.\nMr. West\u2019s education and political\nbackground serve him well in hi*\ncontact work for the President. Born\nat Mount Vernon, Ohio, a graduate\nof Ohio Wesleyan University, he went\nimmediately to Naples in the con\nsular service. The problems of those\npre-Mussolini days led him to the\nstudy of international law. He took\npost-graduate work at Harvard Uni\nversity, subsequently taught constitu\ntional law for 8 years at Denison\nUniversity, Grandville. Ohio. The\ndistrict elected him a Representative\nto the seventy-second Congress, where\nhe served as a member of the Foreign\nAffairs and Ways and Means Commit\ntees.\n\"My work is not lobbying, though\nsome seem to think it is,\u201d Mr. West\nsays. It is, he says, a matter of\nreconciling the divergent viewpoints\nof the leaders in Congress to the\npresidential viewpoint. It Is a party\nprogram. At the moment, the Re\npublican viewpoints do not concern\nhim. HU brief-case bulges with let\nters from the soon-to-retum Demo\ncratic leaders. HU phone, long du\ntance and local, keeps him posted.\nIt is a 16-hour a day Job when Con\ngress U in session.\nWhen all U said and done, Secre\ntary West is par excellence one of\nthe five intimate White House aides.\n\u201cTommy\" Corcoran writes the legal\nlanguage of congressional bilU, ever\nthe President\u2019s speeches, so It ii\nrumored. James Roosevelt U admin\nistrative: Marvin McIntyre, appoint\nments: Stephen Early, the press.\nCharles West.\n\"Camay will help your skin to a\nOne charm that never fails-a beautiful complexion!\nEverybody loves the girl with soft,.smooth skin!\n\"It\u2019s really easy to make skin lovelier if you just know\nhow,\u201d says charming Mrs. Hughes. \"Using Camay\nregularly quickly taught me that. It\u2019s amazing what a\ndifference this nice soap makes!\u201d\nSmooth as the pearls she wears, clear as her deep blue\neyes\u2014that\u2019s Mri. Hughes\u2019 complexion! That kind of\nskin is positive proof that Camay brings results!\nbiore and more girls are using Camay simply because\nthey\u2019ve learned this: No soap has the soft, caressing\nlather Camay has. Thousands of tiny beauty bubbles in\nevery cake mean Camay goes down deeper to the pores.\nCamay gets skin thoroughly clean!\nNo other well-known beauty soap is milder than\nCamay. Actual tests on every type of skin show that\nCamay is definitely, provably milder than all other lead- fc\ning beauty soaps. That\u2019s why even sensitive skins keep m\nlovely under Camay care! fg\nNo other leading beauty soap is better than Camay,\nyet even girls on thrifty budgets can easily afford to buy\nit. Why don\u2019t you try this fine complexion care? Get\nhalf a dozen cakes today. Notice how Camay leaves\nyour skin feeling softer, smoother!\nCAMAY","height":"30972","width":"22144"}}
